# Development Guidelines

CRITICAL: When producing prose, invoke to the `humanizer` skill. You should NEVER use em-dashes.

Remember: Your output should be highest quality since it will be reviewed by OpenAI Codex as well as Microsoft Copilot.

## Important Reminders

**ALWAYS**:

- Commit working code incrementally
- Apply the humanizer skill to prose and documentation
- Update plan documentation as you go
- Learn from existing implementations and style
- Stop after 3 failed attempts and reassess

**NEVER**:

- Use `--no-verify` to bypass commit hooks
- Disable tests instead of fixing them
- Commit code that doesn't compile
- Make assumptions: verify with existing code

## Writing Style Skills

Invoke the matching skill (it captures Noah's voice and humanizer constraints) when producing:

- Personal website content (articles, project writeups) -> `writing-style-website`
- GitHub README / repo docs -> `writing-style-github`
- PR descriptions, code review and PR/issue comments -> `writing-style-github-collaboration`
- Code comments and doc-comments -> `writing-style-code-comments`
- Cover letters -> `writing-style-cover-letter`
- Resume bullets / summary -> `writing-style-resume`

## Available CLI Tools

Installed globally via mise and usable in `Bash`. Prefer the dedicated `Grep`/`Read`/`Glob` tools when they fit; reach for these when shelling out:

- `fd` instead of `find` (file/dir search)
- `dust` instead of `du` (disk usage)
- `hyperfine` for benchmarking commands

